success.question_text: What is the probability that this spinner will land on red?
success.question_hint:
• The spinner has 12 edges.
  • Count the number of edges for the green area and express this as a fraction of the total edges.

stimulus_1.text: This spinner is used in a game.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

In probability you need to consider whether the events are equally likely. For example, although there are only two sectors on this spinner, they are not the same size so there is a greater chance of landing on green.

success.question_text: If a member of the social committee is selected at random, what is the probability that he or she is in year 8?
success.question_hint:
• Work out the total number of students on the committee.
  • Write the number of year 8 students as a simplified fraction of the total students.

stimulus_1.text: A social committee consists of one student from year 7, four from year 8, five from year 9 and two from year 10.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The probability of an event is equal to the number of times that event occurs out of the total number of possible outcomes.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Data Representation and Analysis
success.question_hint:
• The mode is the most popular score.
  • Using a dot plot, it is the score with the highest column.

stimulus_1.text: A dot plot was drawn to illustrate the results when a die was tossed a number of times:

review_3.column_1_text:
There are six 4s, more than any other number.

The mode is 4.

Tip

The mode is the score with the highest frequency. It is the score that happens the most often.

success.question_text: What is the probability that the card shows a cow?
success.question_hint:
• Count the number of cards with cows.
  • Write this number as a fraction of 12 and then simplify the fraction.

stimulus_2.text: She placed the cards in a hat and then pulled one out without looking.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The probability of an event is equal to the number of times the event occurs out of the total number of possible outcomes.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• Work out the total of the seven tests.
  • Add the result in the eighth test and then divide by 8.

stimulus_1.text: Cameron has an average (mean) mark of 85 for his last seven tests. In his eighth test he scored 61.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The mean is another name for the measure commonly called the average. To find the mean, divide the sum of the scores by the number of scores.

success.question_text: How many matches did the team play in the competition?
success.question_hint:
• The table shows 4 matches with 0 goals, 5 matches with 1 goal, and so on.
  • You need to add the heights of each of the columns.

stimulus_1.text: The graph shows the number of goals scored by a soccer team in each of its matches in a competition:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Read the question carefully as well as any information given in the graph.

success.question_text: What is the median of these scores?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• The median is the middle score.
  • You need to first rearrange the scores in order.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The median is the middle score when the scores are arranged in order. If there is an odd number of scores, the median is the middle score. If there is an even number of scores, the median is the average of the two middle scores.

success.question_text: How many more women than men preferred music?
success.question_hint:
• Find the missing score in the table by subtracting the three numbers from 150.
  • Find the difference between the two scores in the music column.

stimulus_1.text: A survey was taken of 150 shoppers to see whether they preferred music or no music in the shopping centre. Some of the results are shown in the table below:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Read all the information carefully. Don’t rush into answering. Take time to think.

success.question_hint:
• Count the number of pegs in each basket.
  • One-quarter of the pegs need to be red and one-third need to be blue.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When checking each option to find the correct one, it is a good idea to check all the options, just to be sure, even if you think you have found the right one. A quick mental check is all that is needed.

success.question_text: How many hours in total did the group spend in the library?
success.question_hint:
• Multiply the numbers in each row.
  • Add these results to give a total number of hours.

stimulus_1.text: A group of students were asked how many hours they had spent in the library during the last week. The results are shown in the table:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Take time to think. Don’t rush into answering a question.

success.question_text:
What is the range?

Type the number of centimetres in the box below without the cm sign, e.g. 13 for 13 cm.
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Data Representation and Analysis
success.question_hint:
• The first row gives the smallest number of 118.
  • The bottom row has the large numbers.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The range is the difference between the highest and lowest scores.

success.question_text:
Russell now chooses a door.

What is the probability that he wins a prize?
success.question_hint:
• Count the remaining unopened doors.
  • Work out the number of cash prizes not already chosen and write as a fraction.

stimulus_1.text: In a game show on television, contestants choose one door from 12. There is a prize behind four of the doors. Two have been opened, one of which had a prize.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The probability of an event is equal to the number of times that event occurs out of the total number of possible outcomes.

success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Chance and Data / Mean, Mode and Median
success.question_hint:
• The mean is the average and the mode the most popular score.
  • The median is the middle score and the range the difference between the highest and the lowest scores.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

The mean is the measure commonly called the average. The mode is the score with the highest frequency. The median is the middle score. The range is the difference between the highest and lowest scores.

success.question_text: How many people preferred to watch tennis?
success.question_hint:
• The total of the angles is 360°.
  • Work out the fraction for tennis and multiply this by the total number in the group.

stimulus_1.text: A group of 250 people were asked which of five sports they preferred to watch. The results are shown in the sector graph:

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The angle at the centre of a sector in a sector graph tells you what fraction of the whole is represented by that sector. The fraction is the number of degrees in the sector out of 360°.

success.question_hint:
• There are three correct statements listed.
  • Work through each statement by checking the data displayed in the table.

stimulus_1.text: The table shows the populations of four towns at five-year intervals:

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

It is not always necessary to work through every option. A quick mental check of the options might give you a good idea which one is correct.

choice_1.label: The population of Birdtown was greater in 1993 than the population of Appley in 2008.

choice_2.label: The population of Cheeseton increased the least over the fifteen years.

choice_3.label: The population of Daisyville increased more between 2003 and 2008 than at any other time.

choice_4.label: The town whose population increased the most between 1993 and 1998 was Appley.

success.question_text: If 56 chose red, how many chose blue?
success.question_hint:
• There are 4 red parts and 3 blue parts.
  • If 4 parts equals 56, find 1 part, then find 3 parts.

stimulus_1.text: A number of students were asked to nominate which of four colours for a logo they preferred. The results are shown in the divided bar chart:

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

Read all the information carefully and work logically, step by step, through a problem.
